{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504784"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2367"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2367"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.03,0.11,0.28,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91434"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2367"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75113"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3348"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31249"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91434"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a three month history of persistent upper burning abdominal pain. The pain is worse after eating and lying down, at a 7/10 intensity. The pain is often associated with multiple episodes of diarrhoea with no blood or mucus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESix months ago she underwent an upper endoscopy for similar symptoms and several gastric ulcers across her gastric pylorus and the first part of her duodenum were found. Thick gastric folds were noted. A biopsy was negative for Helicobacter pylori.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has recently increased her dose of omeprazole and is taking over-the-counter antacids. These have proven ineffective for her gastric pain, even though she takes them regularly. Her abdomen is soft but tender in the epigastrium. A faecal occult blood test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urea breath test","Helicobacter pylori serology","CT abdomen and pelvis","Gastroscopy","Fasting serum gastrin level"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an uncommon condition, in such cases of treatment-resistant peptic ulceration, the possible diagnosis of a gastrinoma (Zollinger-Ellison syndrome) must be considered. This patient symptoms which would fit well, in terms of persistent ulcer symptoms despite increasing doses of the proton pump inhibitor. The diarrhoea symptoms are suggestive of high gastric acid secretion. Before a gastrinoma can be considered, possible NSAID use and medication compliance must be assessed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe urea breath test is a good screening tool for H. pylori. However, the gold standard for detecting H. pylori is by biopsy which was already performed and was negative. There is no need for a screening tool when the diagnostic test is already negative.\u00a0Likewise, serology is also likely to be negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst it would be reasonable to repeat the endoscopy, all this will do is to confirm the presence of ulcers - it will not establish the cause of the ulcer. What is required is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum gastrin\u003C/strong\u003E estimation. If this is sufficiently elevated to suggest the presence of a gastrinoma, then a CT scan of the abdomen could be considered, looking for the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A gastrinoma is a rare, but well recognised cause of peptic ulcer disease."],"references":["Isenberg JI, Walsh JH, Grossman MI. Zollinger-Ellison syndrome. Gastroenterology 1973; 65:140.","Ellison EC, Johnson JA. The Zollinger-Ellison syndrome: a comprehensive review of historical, scientific, and clinical considerations. Curr Probl Surg 2009; 46:13."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2367"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75113"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T19:41:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T19:41:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2367"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91434"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{